<TEI xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" version="5.0">
    <teiHeader type="text">
        <fileDesc>
            <titleStmt>
                <title>The Oxen</title>
                <author>Thomas Hardy</author>
            </titleStmt>
            <publicationStmt>
                <date>1917</date>
            </publicationStmt>
            <sourceDesc default="false">
                <p/>
            </sourceDesc>
        </fileDesc>
    </teiHeader><text><body>
         <lg n="1" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/3/4/3)" rhyme="abab" org="uniform" sample="complete"
                part="N">
                <l n="1" part="N" met="-+-+-+-+" real="+-+-+--+">
                    <seg met="-+" real="+" part="N">Christ<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">mas Eve, </seg>
                    <caesura/>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">and twelve </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">of the <rhyme label="a">clock.</rhyme></seg>
                </l>
                <note anchored="true"> The stressing of this line is pretty straightforward, but a
                    question may arise how to divide it into feet. It might seem simplest to make
                    three trochees followed by an iamb, yet this choice would be misleading, since
                    later lines will establish the meter of the whole poem as iambic. Better
                    acknowledge that rising rhythm from the very start, even at the initial
                    inconvenience of postulating the catalexis of a one-syllable first foot.
                    First-position trochees will be frequent in the coming lines, and at times even
                    poignant in their underdog resistance to the iambic norm and what Hardy makes it
                    stand for.  That's another reason for not letting them run rampant here. </note>
                <l n="2" part="N" met="-+-+-+" real="+--+--+">
                    <seg met="-+" real="^+" part="N">"Now they </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">are all </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">on their <rhyme label="b">knees,"</rhyme></seg>
                </l>
                <l n="3" part="N" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+-+--+--+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">An el<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">der said </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">as we sat </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">in a <rhyme label="a">flock</rhyme></seg>
                </l>
                <space/>
                <l n="4" part="N" met="-+-+-+" real="--+--+-+">
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">By the em<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">bers in hearth<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">side <rhyme label="b">ease.</rhyme></seg>
                </l>
            </lg>
        <lg n="2" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/3/4/3)" rhyme="cdcd" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                <l n="5" part="N" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+--+++-+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">We pic<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">tured the meek </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="++" part="N">mild crea<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">tures <rhyme label="c">where</rhyme></seg>
                </l><l n="6" part="N" met="-+-+-+" real="-+--+-+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">They dwelt </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">in their straw<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">y <rhyme label="d">pen,</rhyme></seg>
                </l><l n="7" part="N" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+--+-+--+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">Nor did </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">it oc<sb part="N"/>cur </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">to one </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">of us <rhyme label="c">there</rhyme></seg>
                </l><space/><l n="8" part="N" met="-+-+-+" real="-+--+-+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">To doubt </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">they were kneel<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">ing <rhyme label="d">then.</rhyme></seg>
                </l>
        </lg>
        <lg n="3" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/3/4/3)" rhyme="efef" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                    <l n="9" part="N" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+-+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">So fair </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">a fan<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">cy few </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">would <rhyme label="e">weave</rhyme></seg>
                </l><l n="10" part="N" met="-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">In these </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">years! <caesura/> Yet, </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">I <rhyme label="f">feel,</rhyme></seg>
                    <note anchored="real"> The first three words of this line furnish a nice example
                        of how colloquial speech pattern trumps the prosodic rules of thumb. The
                        rules say that "years," a monosyllabic noun, should take stress, while the
                        common adjective "these" should not.  But not this time.</note>
                </l><l n="11" part="N" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+-+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">If some<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">one said </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">on Christ<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">mas <rhyme label="e">Eve,</rhyme></seg>
                </l><space/>
            <l n="12" part="N" met="-+-+-+" real="+--+-+">
                    "<seg met="-+" real="+-" part="N">"Come; <caesura/>see </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">the ox<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">en <rhyme label="f">kneel</rhyme></seg>
                </l>
                <note anchored="true"> This homely line grows beautiful through the slightest of
                    rhythmic departures from the iambics that have entirely governed stanza 3. A
                    trochaic first foot lets this line skip back prosodically to resume the relaxed
                    pattern of double-slacks that was so frequent in stanzas 1 and 2, back when
                    belief came easy too. Hardy makes the poem do some complicated remembering, way
                    down in its personal and cultural bones. </note>
        </lg>
        <lg n="4" type="quatrain" met="-+(4/3/4/3)" rhyme="ghgh" org="uniform" sample="complete" part="N">
                <l n="13" part="N" met="-+-+-+-+" real="--+-+--+-+">
                    "<seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">In the lone<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">ly bar<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" real="--+" part="N">ton by yon<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">der <rhyme label="g">coomb</rhyme></seg>
                </l><l n="14" part="N" met="-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">Our child<sb part="N"/></seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">hood used </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">to <rhyme label="h">know,"</rhyme></seg>
                </l><l n="15" part="N" met="-+-+-+-+" real="-+-+-+-+|+-+--+-+|+--+-+-+">
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">I should </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">go with </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">him in </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">the <rhyme label="g">gloom,</rhyme></seg>
                </l>
                <note anchored="true"> The exquisite ambivalence that Hardy expresses here about the
                    lost faith of his childhood opens several valid options for scanning this line.
                    4B4V permits a trochee in the first foot and even the second.  But doesn't the
                    whole finale read better if that stumbling effect is reserved for the line to
                    come? Let line 15 be strictly iambic like line 14, figuring the willing trance, or
                    suspension of disbelief, from which line 16 then awakens into mere but honest hope. </note>
            <space/><l n="16" part="N" met="-+-+-+" real="+--+-+">
                    <seg met="-+" real="+-" part="N">Hop<sb part="N"/>ing </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">it might </seg>
                    <seg met="-+" part="N">be <rhyme label="h">so.</rhyme></seg>
                </l></lg></body></text></TEI>